Case and point, Bojack Horseman, Animal Crossing, Elder Scrolls, old/new Disney cartoons, Zootopia etc. How do they have clear elements of anthropomorphic animals yet are accepted by mainstream culture. Yet furry culture is usually reviled.

So the question I have is. When does it count as furry?

This is mostly theory seeing there is no fixed definition on what counts as a 'furry'. It's boiling my brain as I'm sitting on a novel draft that heavily features anthros and I'm deciding could it work outside the furry fandom.

Anonymous Thu 04 Mar 2021 05:31:02 No.36798637 Report
Quoted By: >>36804131
>>36795210
It's not about when it's furry and when it's not. Most people - even people who love stuff like Zootopia - will admit that it is technically "furry," or at least could very easy be incorporated into the subculture. I remember everyone mentioning furries when that movie came out, yet most still enjoyed it.

The three big factors relating to mainstream appeal are:

1. Is it made by a furry?
2. Is it sexual in any way?
3. Is it good?

For media like Zootopia and Animal Crossing, the answers are no for 1-2, and yes for 3, making it accessible. But BoJack Horseman shows people will even accept sexualized stuff if it's more for story purposes and not wank material. (BoJack also shows people will accept it even if it isn't good lol)

Regardless of if you are a furry or not, try to produce HMOFA/anthro stuff as if you weren't. Just treat it as an artistic filter of sorts, then, as people get used to it, you can start phasing in more conceptually relevant stuff. And, of course, making it funny will always endear people to it much quicker.

And given that western culture has a couple generations forth of Disney/Star Trek/Star Wars, it's not like the average person hasn't seen non-human characters before.
>2. Is it sexual in any way?
There are lines. Was Space Jam a little, um, flirty? Pretty much tradition at this point in western animation. A better way to look at it - is that all that defines the female character's personality beyond their anthro-ness?
>3. Is it good?
If the first two are met, then you're not writing/producing straight up fetish fuel. So
>Just treat it as an artistic filter of sorts
Becomes using it to communicate by trope. Bugs Bunny had plenty in common with Renard the Fox, and stole as well from B'rer Rabbit.
